#Text=PART II
#Text=In point of fact , as Percy Beaumont would have said , Mrs. Westgate disembarked on the 18th of May on the British coast .
#Text=She was accompanied by her sister , but she was not attended by any other member of her family .

#Text=To the deprivation of her husband ’s society Mrs. Westgate was , however , habituated ; she had made half a dozen journeys to Europe without him , and she now accounted for his absence , to interrogative friends on this side of the Atlantic , by allusion to the regrettable but conspicuous fact that in America there was no leisure class .

#Text=The two ladies came up to London and alighted at Jones ’s Hotel , where Mrs. Westgate , who had made on former occasions the most agreeable impression at this establishment , received an obsequious greeting .

#Text=Bessie Alden had felt much excited about coming to England ; she had expected the “ associations ” would be very charming , that it would be an infinite pleasure to rest her eyes upon the things she had read about in the poets and historians .

#Text=She was very fond of the poets and historians , of the picturesque , of the past , of retrospect , of mementos and reverberations of greatness ; so that on coming into the English world , where strangeness and familiarity would go hand in hand , she was prepared for a multitude of fresh emotions .

#Text=They began very promptly -- these tender , fluttering sensations ; they began with the sight of the beautiful English landscape , whose dark richness was quickened and brightened by the season ; with the carpeted fields and flowering hedgerows , as she looked at them from the window of the train ; with the spires of the rural churches peeping above the rook-haunted treetops ; with the oak-studded parks , the ancient homes , the cloudy light , the speech , the manners , the thousand differences .
#Text=Mrs. Westgate ’s impressions had , of course , much less novelty and keenness , and she gave but a wandering attention to her sister ’s ejaculations and rhapsodies .
#Text=“ You know my enjoyment of England is not so intellectual as Bessie ’s , ” she said to several of her friends in the course of her visit to this country .
#Text=“ And yet if it is not intellectual , I ca n’t say it is physical .
#Text=I do n’t think I can quite say what it is , my enjoyment of England . ”

#Text=When once it was settled that the two ladies should come abroad and should spend a few weeks in England on their way to the Continent , they of course exchanged a good many allusions to their London acquaintance .
#Text=“ It will certainly be much nicer having friends there , ” Bessie Alden had said one day as she sat on the sunny deck of the steamer at her sister ’s feet on a large blue rug .
#Text=“ Whom do you mean by friends ? ” Mrs. Westgate asked .
#Text=“ All those English gentlemen whom you have known and entertained .
#Text=Captain Littledale , for instance .
#Text=And Lord Lambeth and Mr. Beaumont , ” added Bessie Alden .
#Text=“ Do you expect them to give us a very grand reception ? ”
#Text=Bessie reflected a moment ; she was addicted , as we know , to reflection .
#Text=“ Well , yes . ”
#Text=“ My poor , sweet child , ” murmured her sister .
#Text=“ What have I said that is so silly ? ” asked Bessie .
#Text=“ You are a little too simple ; just a little .
#Text=It is very becoming , but it pleases people at your expense . ”
#Text=“ I am certainly too simple to understand you , ” said Bessie .
#Text=“ Shall I tell you a story ? ” asked her sister .
#Text=“ If you would be so good .
#Text=That is what they do to amuse simple people . ”
#Text=Mrs. Westgate consulted her memory , while her companion sat gazing at the shining sea .
#Text=“ Did you ever hear of the Duke of Green-Erin ? ”
#Text=“ I think not , ” said Bessie .
#Text=“ Well , it ’s no matter , ” her sister went on .
#Text=“ It ’s a proof of my simplicity . ”
#Text=“ My story is meant to illustrate that of some other people , ” said Mrs. Westgate .
#Text=“ The Duke of Green-Erin is what they call in England a great swell , and some five years ago he came to America .
#Text=He spent most of his time in New York , and in New York he spent his days and his nights at the Butterworths ’ .
#Text=You have heard , at least , of the Butterworths .
#Text=BIEN .
#Text=They did everything in the world for him -- they turned themselves inside out .
#Text=They gave him a dozen dinner parties and balls and were the means of his being invited to fifty more .
#Text=At first he used to come into Mrs. Butterworth ’s box at the opera in a tweed traveling suit ; but someone stopped that .
#Text=At any rate , he had a beautiful time , and they parted the best friends in the world .
#Text=Two years elapse , and the Butterworths come abroad and go to London .
#Text=The first thing they see in all the papers --
#Text=in England those things are in the most prominent place -- is that the Duke of Green-Erin has arrived in town for the Season .
#Text=They wait a little , and then Mr. Butterworth -- as polite as ever -- goes and leaves a card .
#Text=They wait a little more ; the visit is not returned ; they wait three weeks -- silence de mort -- the Duke gives no sign .
#Text=The Butterworths see a lot of other people , put down the Duke of Green-Erin as a rude , ungrateful man , and forget all about him .
#Text=One fine day they go to Ascot Races , and there they meet him face to face .
#Text=He stares a moment and then comes up to Mr. Butterworth , taking something from his pocketbook -- something which proves to be a banknote .
#Text=‘ I ’m glad to see you , Mr. Butterworth , ’ he says , ‘ so that I can pay you that ten pounds I lost to you in New York .
#Text=I saw the other day you remembered our bet ; here are the ten pounds , Mr. Butterworth .
#Text=Goodbye , Mr. Butterworth . ’
#Text=And off he goes , and that ’s the last they see of the Duke of Green-Erin . ”
